answer.p:
3. In this situation, A is diagonalizable if and only if the 3-eigenspace is a plane. For example, the matrix


                        \mat{
                        3 1 0;
                        0 3 0;
                        0 0 5
                        }
                        \text{is not diagonalizable, but}
                        \mat{
                        3 0 0;
                        0 3 0;
                        0 0 5
                        }
                        \text{is.}

ol.li:
The 0-eigenspace is the null space of A, which we compute:


                                \mat{1 1 1; 1 1 1; 0 0 0} \longsquiggly[rref] \mat{1 1 1; 0 0 0; 0 0 0} \longsquiggly[] \syseq{x=-y-z;y=y;z=z}   


                                \longsquiggly[] \vec{x y z} = y\vec{-1 1 0} + z\vec{-1 0 1}


                        Thus a basis for the 0-eigenspace is
                        \bigl\{\vec{-1 1 0}, \vec{-1 0 1}\bigr\}
                        Next we compute a basis for the 2-eigenspace, which is \Nul(A-2I):


                                \mat{-1 1 1;1 -1 1; 0 0 -2} \longsquiggly[rref] \mat{1 -1 0;0 0 1; 0 0 0} \longsquiggly[] \syseq{x=y;y=y;z=0}


                                \longsquiggly[] \vec{x y z} = y \vec{1 1 0}


                        Thus a basis for the 2-eigenspace is
                        \bigl\{\vec{1 1 0}\bigr\}
